Hello. Our drive station/robot disengages during teleop. Error is “Drive Station not keeping up with protocol rates”. Any suggestions would be appreciated. Thanks.

The error was added this year to prevent a situation in which the controls packets were significantly delayed going to the rio, but still arrived with enough frequency to feed the watchdog. This condition will not disable the robot on the field, only in the shop, but it is generally indicative of potential issue.

First place I would look is driver station CPU load, ensure other programs and services are not running if they are not needed, and plug in your driver station as most laptops throttle the CPU on battery power.

The next place would be rio CPU load, if that’s high it can also cause issues, look into reducing the CPU load of your code.

Finally, it might be high network latency but given the simplicity of the robot network this is unlikely, but if you have a noisy WiFi environment or other network congestion you can run into issues.

Really appreciate the answer. Super helpful. Curious, but I realize might not be possible to answer in a general way, how would one reduce the CPU load of the code?

DS logs should have rio cpu load to tell you if its even a problem, so check there first.

The question of how to actually reduce load is a somewhat complicated one, but basically it boils down to make the code do less. Things like vision on the rio will be a massive load, any sort of complex processing you are doing on the robot. High refresh rate tasks can cause high load, large loops, things like that
